Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.670 --> 00:00:07.865
Okay, what I did last time was
describe to you a certain heat

00:00:07.865 --> 00:00:12.941
engine called the Carnot engine.
So, let me refresh your memory

00:00:12.941 --> 00:00:18.564
on what that was.
The whole engine consisted of a

00:00:18.564 --> 00:00:23.890
gas at some pressure and some
volume.

00:00:23.890 --> 00:00:28.895
And the gas was subject to a
cycle, and the cycle went like

00:00:28.895 --> 00:00:31.894
this.
You start at some point

00:00:31.894 --> 00:00:36.474
A, you expand at a
certain temperature

00:00:36.474 --> 00:00:40.014
T_1,
isothermally,

00:00:40.014 --> 00:00:43.970
until you come to point
B.

00:00:43.970 --> 00:00:47.892
So, the way you should imagine
that is that this gas is placed

00:00:47.892 --> 00:00:51.622
on a reservoir whose temperature
is frozen, I mean stuck at

00:00:51.622 --> 00:00:54.829
T_1.
Reservoirs never change the

00:00:54.829 --> 00:00:57.702
temperature.
And what you do is you lift one

00:00:57.702 --> 00:01:01.364
grain after another of sand,
so you let the gas expand,

00:01:01.364 --> 00:01:05.361
but you don't let it cool down.
The minute it tries to cool

00:01:05.361 --> 00:01:09.056
some heat will go from below to
maintain the temperature and

00:01:09.056 --> 00:01:12.000
start at that volume and end at
that volume.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.352
During this process,
some amount of heat

00:01:15.352 --> 00:01:18.620
Q_1 enters the
gas.

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:22.457
Next thing you do,
you let the gas expand some

00:01:22.457 --> 00:01:26.549
more, but now you let it expand
adiabatically.

00:01:26.549 --> 00:01:31.842
Adiabatic means you put the
whole thing in a heat insulating

00:01:31.842 --> 00:01:35.430
material, so no heat can go in
or out.

00:01:35.430 --> 00:01:38.560
Now, you can see if it expands,
it's going to have to pay for

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:41.900
it with its own internal energy,
so the temperature will drop.

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:45.324
So, you wait till it drops to a
lower temperature

00:01:45.324 --> 00:01:48.677
T_2,
then you go backwards like

00:01:48.677 --> 00:01:51.115
this;
that's when you start

00:01:51.115 --> 00:01:55.989
compressing the gas by putting
some grains of sand back,

00:01:55.989 --> 00:02:00.096
but this time the gas is kept
in a lower temperature on top of

00:02:00.096 --> 00:02:03.260
a temperature reservoir
T_2,

00:02:03.260 --> 00:02:09.639
and you drop more sand on it to
compress it, that is this part.

00:02:09.639 --> 00:02:13.227
During this portion,
heat will actually be rejected

00:02:13.227 --> 00:02:15.770
by the gas.
Why is heat rejected?

00:02:15.770 --> 00:02:18.010
Because normally,
when you compress a gas,

00:02:18.010 --> 00:02:20.633
you're doing work on it,
the energy should go up,

00:02:20.633 --> 00:02:23.530
the energy goes up,
the temperature should go up;

00:02:23.530 --> 00:02:25.104
but you're not letting the
temperature go up,

00:02:25.104 --> 00:02:26.535
you're forcing it to have the
temperature

00:02:26.535 --> 00:02:29.625
T_2.
So, it will reject heat into

00:02:29.625 --> 00:02:31.775
this heat bath.
And finally,

00:02:31.775 --> 00:02:36.106
you come back to the starting
point by further compression,

00:02:36.106 --> 00:02:38.943
but adiabatic,
and adiabatic means it's

00:02:38.943 --> 00:02:41.780
insulated from the outside
world;

00:02:41.780 --> 00:02:44.889
no heat flow.
So, there are four parts.

00:02:44.889 --> 00:02:49.633
There are two things you have
to notice about the Carnot

00:02:49.633 --> 00:02:51.436
engine.
In fact, let me draw a

00:02:51.436 --> 00:02:55.011
schematic of the Carnot engine.
This is the standard way people

00:02:55.011 --> 00:02:57.312
draw that.
The engine takes some heat

00:02:57.312 --> 00:03:01.099
Q_1 from the
furnace at T_1,

00:03:01.099 --> 00:03:03.720
it has some
Q_2 rejected at

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:06.828
the exhaust, which is at
T_2 and it

00:03:06.828 --> 00:03:09.509
delivers a certain amount of
work which,

00:03:09.509 --> 00:03:11.366
by the Law of Conservation of
Energy, has to be

00:03:11.366 --> 00:03:12.940
Q_1 -
Q_2.

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:20.233
Do you understand that?
The work done by the gas equal

00:03:20.233 --> 00:03:22.270
to that.
And who paid for it?

00:03:22.270 --> 00:03:24.773
It is the reservoir,
upper reservoir furnished the

00:03:24.773 --> 00:03:27.685
heat, some heat was rejected
downstairs and the difference

00:03:27.685 --> 00:03:29.320
between the two is the work.

00:03:33.830 --> 00:03:38.251
Now, we call this a cyclic
process because at the end of

00:03:38.251 --> 00:03:41.949
the day, the gases come back to
where it is.

00:03:41.949 --> 00:03:44.639
That's very important,
if you want to make an engine,

00:03:44.639 --> 00:03:47.901
it's not enough to convert;
the whole purpose of heat

00:03:47.901 --> 00:03:52.060
engines was to burn something
and get some work out of it.

00:03:52.060 --> 00:03:53.720
But you don't want it to be a
one shot thing.

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:56.437
You want to be able to do it
over and over and over again and

00:03:56.437 --> 00:03:59.110
you can do that with this engine
because after the cycle,

00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:01.722
it's back to where it started
and you can do this any number

00:04:01.722 --> 00:04:04.837
of times.
Now, we define an efficiency

00:04:04.837 --> 00:04:09.061
for this engine,
which is what you get divided

00:04:09.061 --> 00:04:12.978
by what you pay for.
What you get from the engine is

00:04:12.978 --> 00:04:16.383
of course, the work W and
what you pay for is the coal

00:04:16.383 --> 00:04:19.050
that you burn which is
Q_1.

00:04:19.050 --> 00:04:21.618
Now, writing W as
Q_1 -

00:04:21.618 --> 00:04:24.431
Q_2 you can write
this as 1 minus

00:04:24.431 --> 00:04:27.550
Q_2 over
Q_1.

00:04:27.550 --> 00:04:31.403
This is true for any engine.
Any engine, even if it's not a

00:04:31.403 --> 00:04:34.490
Carnot engine;
with the Law of Conservation of

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:37.620
Energy you can write something
like this.

00:04:37.620 --> 00:04:41.042
Anyway, let me say with the
Carnot engine I got this as the

00:04:41.042 --> 00:04:44.935
efficiency.
Now, why is the efficiency not

00:04:44.935 --> 00:04:46.286
100%?
That's because

00:04:46.286 --> 00:04:48.050
Q_2 is not
zero.

00:04:48.050 --> 00:04:51.689
You can say why are we building
a stupid engine that rejects

00:04:51.689 --> 00:04:54.018
some heat?
Why not just use all of it in

00:04:54.018 --> 00:04:56.703
some other fashion,
and that's what we're going to

00:04:56.703 --> 00:04:59.195
talk about,
but assuming that the engine

00:04:59.195 --> 00:05:01.230
operates between two
temperatures,

00:05:01.230 --> 00:05:05.360
the furnace temperature and the
ambient atmospheric temperature,

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:08.158
you can calculate the
efficiency for this engine by

00:05:08.158 --> 00:05:10.620
actually calculating
Q_2 and

00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:13.920
Q_1.
That's a simple problem of

00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:17.940
integrating the work done and
going from here to here.

00:05:17.940 --> 00:05:22.229
Do you remember that?
1 - nRT_1

00:05:22.229 --> 00:05:28.037
log V_B over
V_A and

00:05:28.037 --> 00:05:32.640
downstairs you have NR
T_2 log

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:38.009
V_C over
V_D.

00:05:38.009 --> 00:05:40.000
Again, you've got to remember
why that is true.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.002
When you go from A to
B there is no change in

00:05:43.002 --> 00:05:45.589
internal energy because
temperature is the same.

00:05:45.589 --> 00:05:47.828
Therefore, the work done and
the heat import are equal

00:05:47.828 --> 00:05:49.812
numerically, so
Q_2 is the work

00:05:49.812 --> 00:05:52.220
done and Q_1 is
the work done there.

00:05:52.220 --> 00:05:55.022
So, that's what I got.
Then, I did a little bit of

00:05:55.022 --> 00:05:57.993
calculation to show you by using
the fact that B and

00:05:57.993 --> 00:05:59.940
C are on an adiabatic
curve,

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:03.508
A and D are on an
adiabatic curve,

00:06:03.508 --> 00:06:06.089
that these logs actually
cancel,

00:06:06.089 --> 00:06:07.960
these guys of course,
cancel to give the final result

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:10.010
1 minus T_2
over T_1.

00:06:10.010 --> 00:06:13.516
That's the bottom line.
I don't care what else you

00:06:13.516 --> 00:06:17.180
remember but this is something I
need for today's discussion.

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:20.700
Efficiency of the Carnot engine
is 1 minus T_2

00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:22.290
over T_1.

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:32.441
Okay now, you can say why I'd
be interested in this very

00:06:32.441 --> 00:06:36.829
primitive engine containing a
cylinder and gas and so on.

00:06:36.829 --> 00:06:39.380
Okay, this efficiency of this
stupid engine,

00:06:39.380 --> 00:06:41.990
I'm sure people can build a
better engine.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:45.896
So, here is Carnot's claim.
Mr.

00:06:45.896 --> 00:06:55.000
Carnot say,s "No engine can
beat my engine."

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.859
Okay that's his claim.
By "beat my engine" he means,

00:06:58.859 --> 00:07:02.170
no engine can be more efficient
than my engine.

00:07:02.170 --> 00:07:05.360
And he's going to demonstrate
that.

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:06.899
I'm going to demonstrate that
for you.

00:07:06.899 --> 00:07:08.600
You don't get something for
nothing.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:11.684
It's based on the following
postulate, which I told you last

00:07:11.684 --> 00:07:13.420
time.
I'm just now going to write it;

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:17.101
I will repeat it.
We are going to postulate,

00:07:17.101 --> 00:07:20.414
as the Second Law of
Thermodynamics,

00:07:20.414 --> 00:07:24.389
that it's impossible to find a
process,

00:07:24.389 --> 00:07:28.501
the sole result of which is to
transfer some heat from a cold

00:07:28.501 --> 00:07:31.697
body to a hot body.
We all know you can transfer

00:07:31.697 --> 00:07:35.149
heat from a cold body to a hot
body in a refrigerator.

00:07:35.149 --> 00:07:37.326
You take heat out of the
freezer and dump it into the

00:07:37.326 --> 00:07:40.269
room;
no one says that's wrong.

00:07:40.269 --> 00:07:42.594
But that's not the sole effect,
because you get an electric

00:07:42.594 --> 00:07:44.878
bill at the end of the month,
because there's a compressor

00:07:44.878 --> 00:07:47.449
doing a lot of work.
The claim is--not--no other

00:07:47.449 --> 00:07:50.610
agency in the end should be
affected in any fashion.

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:53.910
If at the end of the day all
you had was heat flow up hill.

00:07:53.910 --> 00:07:56.915
That's not allowed;
that's a postulate and you have

00:07:56.915 --> 00:07:59.602
to grant him that postulate
which we accept to be

00:07:59.602 --> 00:08:02.798
phenomenologically valid.
But taking that postulate,

00:08:02.798 --> 00:08:06.620
Carnot will now show you that
no engine can beat his engine.

00:08:06.620 --> 00:08:11.314
The key to the whole Carnot
engine is that it is a

00:08:11.314 --> 00:08:15.875
reversible engine.
By reversible engine I mean on

00:08:15.875 --> 00:08:21.079
every step in the Carnot cycle,
let's say going from here to

00:08:21.079 --> 00:08:25.859
here, I can also go backwards.
I can put a grain of sand and

00:08:25.859 --> 00:08:28.953
compress a piston,
or I can take a grain it'll go

00:08:28.953 --> 00:08:31.582
back to where it was.
You're never far from

00:08:31.582 --> 00:08:34.519
equilibrium and if you can go
one way you can go the other

00:08:34.519 --> 00:08:36.403
way.
That also means the Carnot

00:08:36.403 --> 00:08:39.800
engine, starting at the point
A, can go backwards to

00:08:39.800 --> 00:08:43.549
D then C then to
B and then to A.

00:08:43.549 --> 00:08:47.493
If the Carnot engine went
backwards it would look like

00:08:47.493 --> 00:08:51.510
this: it will take heat
Q_1--I'm sorry

00:08:51.510 --> 00:08:54.710
it will take heat
Q_2,

00:08:54.710 --> 00:08:58.290
somebody will give it work
W and it'll reject

00:08:58.290 --> 00:09:01.309
Q_1 at this
temperature.

00:09:01.309 --> 00:09:07.039
This is the Carnot refrigerator
and that's the Carnot engine.

00:09:07.039 --> 00:09:09.281
The Carnot engine and the
refrigerator are the same

00:09:09.281 --> 00:09:10.911
machine;
you just can make it run

00:09:10.911 --> 00:09:15.440
one-way or the opposite way.
That's what we're going to use.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:18.831
So, let me give you a
demonstration that's for--as far

00:09:18.831 --> 00:09:22.158
as I can tell is good enough for
our present purpose,

00:09:22.158 --> 00:09:24.909
that you cannot beat the Carnot
engine.

00:09:24.909 --> 00:09:30.003
So, let us say a Carnot engine
takes some heat,

00:09:30.003 --> 00:09:35.429
say 100 calories,
delivers 20 calories in work,

00:09:35.429 --> 00:09:37.869
rejects 80 calories is
operating between some two

00:09:37.869 --> 00:09:39.699
temperatures
T_1 and

00:09:39.699 --> 00:09:41.480
T_2.
This is the Carnot.

00:09:46.769 --> 00:09:51.139
I am taking a particular
example where the efficiency is

00:09:51.139 --> 00:09:54.408
what, one-fifth.
But don't worry about the fact

00:09:54.408 --> 00:09:56.981
that, yeah, so it's one-fifth,
so one minus

00:09:56.981 --> 00:10:00.350
T_2 over
T_1 should be

00:10:00.350 --> 00:10:03.397
one-fifth.
Now, if you say you have a

00:10:03.397 --> 00:10:07.080
better engine,
you have a better efficiency.

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:11.438
What you really mean is that
your engine can take a 100

00:10:11.438 --> 00:10:15.070
calories and deliver more than
20 calories,

00:10:15.070 --> 00:10:18.515
maybe even deliver 40 calories
and reject only 60 calories,

00:10:18.515 --> 00:10:22.080
but it's also operating between
the same two temperatures.

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:25.735
So, this is your engine.
U for--no,

00:10:25.735 --> 00:10:29.210
Y for your engine,
okay;

00:10:29.210 --> 00:10:31.798
your engine is better than
Carnot's engine,

00:10:31.798 --> 00:10:35.374
okay that's your claim.
You're now going to get shot

00:10:35.374 --> 00:10:37.913
down.
So, how am I going to shoot

00:10:37.913 --> 00:10:41.075
this down?
I am going to run the Carnot

00:10:41.075 --> 00:10:46.014
engine backwards first thing,
then I am going to get a Carnot

00:10:46.014 --> 00:10:50.460
engine which is twice as big as
this Carnot engine,

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:53.792
it's not more efficient,
it has just got twice as much

00:10:53.792 --> 00:10:56.086
gas.
If you take a Carnot engine and

00:10:56.086 --> 00:10:59.300
do the following things,
run it backwards and make it

00:10:59.300 --> 00:11:02.620
twice as big.
What will that Carnot engine do?

00:11:02.620 --> 00:11:07.275
It will look like this;
it will take up 160 calories

00:11:07.275 --> 00:11:11.835
from downstairs,
it will want 40 calories input

00:11:11.835 --> 00:11:15.800
and it'll dump 200 calories
upstairs.

00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:20.331
So, this is a two-times Carnot;
let me put a star saying it's

00:11:20.331 --> 00:11:24.258
Carnot run backwards.
See, it doesn't take any

00:11:24.258 --> 00:11:28.270
special genius to make an engine
bigger.

00:11:28.270 --> 00:11:30.820
It won't be more efficient;
it'll have the same efficiency.

00:11:30.820 --> 00:11:33.083
But if you can build something
with one piston,

00:11:33.083 --> 00:11:35.888
I can make the same design with
a bigger piston or smaller

00:11:35.888 --> 00:11:38.346
piston.
I'm just saying I want it to be

00:11:38.346 --> 00:11:41.190
twice as big for the following
simple reason.

00:11:41.190 --> 00:11:45.280
Your engine's giving out 40
units of work;

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:49.882
my refrigerator needs 40 to run.
So, what we do is we directly

00:11:49.882 --> 00:11:54.350
take the output from your engine
and feed it to my refrigerator.

00:11:54.350 --> 00:11:59.861
Okay, your heat engine makes
work, my refrigerator needs work

00:11:59.861 --> 00:12:05.740
and I've scaled mine so that its
appetite matches your output;

00:12:05.740 --> 00:12:09.485
that's all I've done.
Now, let's draw a box around

00:12:09.485 --> 00:12:14.559
these guys, don't look under the
hood and see what you've got.

00:12:14.559 --> 00:12:17.256
At the end of a full cycle,
when everything is done,

00:12:17.256 --> 00:12:18.842
all the gases,
all the pistons,

00:12:18.842 --> 00:12:21.379
everything has come back to
where it starts.

00:12:21.379 --> 00:12:27.070
But, no need to plug this
gadget into the wall.

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:30.148
You don't have to plug this
into anything because this

00:12:30.148 --> 00:12:33.342
refrigerator is getting the
power from this heat engine,

00:12:33.342 --> 00:12:35.550
so it doesn't need external
power.

00:12:35.550 --> 00:12:39.090
I look at the lower reservoir;
I see 100 calories leaving.

00:12:39.090 --> 00:12:41.620
You see that 60 coming down and
