00:15:11.882 --> 00:15:14.925
than this.
Okay now, let me leave the

00:15:14.925 --> 00:15:20.617
practical domain and go to more
theoretical issues that follow

00:15:20.617 --> 00:15:23.629
from this.
What I want you to notice if

00:15:23.629 --> 00:15:25.751
the following:
for a Carnot engine

00:15:25.751 --> 00:15:29.351
Q_1 over
Q_2 turned out

00:15:29.351 --> 00:15:33.080
to be T_1 over
T_2.

00:15:33.080 --> 00:15:37.373
Right, I did that for you here.
Therefore, I am going to write

00:15:37.373 --> 00:15:40.147
it as follows:
Q_1 over

00:15:40.147 --> 00:15:43.774
T_1 minus
Q_2 over

00:15:43.774 --> 00:15:46.620
T_2 equal to
zero.

00:15:46.620 --> 00:15:51.581
That's just a simple rewrite.
But I am going to write this in

00:15:51.581 --> 00:15:54.740
another rotation.
My cycle had four parts;

00:15:54.740 --> 00:15:56.713
remember, I did this,
then I did this,

00:15:56.713 --> 00:15:58.580
then I did this,
then I did that.

00:15:58.580 --> 00:16:03.266
In this segment I had
Q_1 over

00:16:03.266 --> 00:16:07.098
T_1.
In this segment there was no

00:16:07.098 --> 00:16:09.437
Q_1 or
Q_2,

00:16:09.437 --> 00:16:12.148
there was no Q,
because this is the adiabatic

00:16:12.148 --> 00:16:14.191
process.
In this segment,

00:16:14.191 --> 00:16:17.232
I had minus
Q_2 over

00:16:17.232 --> 00:16:21.878
T_2 and the
last segment I had zero and

00:16:21.878 --> 00:16:25.342
whole thing is zero.
In other words,

00:16:25.342 --> 00:16:28.860
what I'm telling you is the
following.

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:34.074
At every stage,
if you looked at the heat

00:16:34.074 --> 00:16:39.809
absorbed by the system,
in stage i,

00:16:39.809 --> 00:16:44.254
divided by the temperature of
stage i and you added all

00:16:44.254 --> 00:16:48.950
of them you get zero.
My process had four stages.

00:16:48.950 --> 00:16:51.923
Stage 1 is here,
stage 2 is adiabatic,

00:16:51.923 --> 00:16:55.539
state 3 is this,
and stage 4 is zero again.

00:16:55.539 --> 00:17:01.277
In this summation
Q_i is defined

00:17:01.277 --> 00:17:08.927
to be ∆Q_i is
the heat input in stage i

00:17:08.927 --> 00:17:13.230
in the cycle,
or in the process.

00:17:13.230 --> 00:17:16.178
So, we define
Q_2 to be

00:17:16.178 --> 00:17:20.259
positive, even though it was
rejected by the engine,

00:17:20.259 --> 00:17:22.557
but in this summation,
the agreement I make is

00:17:22.557 --> 00:17:25.619
∆Q is positive if the
heat comes into the system,

00:17:25.619 --> 00:17:28.470
∆Q is negative if heat
leaves the system.

00:17:28.470 --> 00:17:34.595
So, why is that important?
Now, this is the heart of the

00:17:34.595 --> 00:17:39.019
whole entropy concept.
Remember I told you there is

00:17:39.019 --> 00:17:42.680
nothing called the heat in a
system.

00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:45.770
You cannot look at a gas and
say that's the amount of heat in

00:17:45.770 --> 00:17:47.509
the system.
Why?

00:17:47.509 --> 00:17:51.649
Because if you take a point
there and say there's some

00:17:51.649 --> 00:17:55.799
amount of heat in the system,
if you go through some kind of

00:17:55.799 --> 00:17:59.372
cycle and come back to the same
point, then since you come back

00:17:59.372 --> 00:18:02.369
to the same point internal
energy doesn't change,

00:18:02.369 --> 00:18:06.423
this is the work done,
therefore, the work done is

00:18:06.423 --> 00:18:09.650
equal to the heat and it is not
zero.

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:13.329
So, in this example what
would've happened is you'd added

00:18:13.329 --> 00:18:17.238
heat Q to the system.
So, if there is some notion of

00:18:17.238 --> 00:18:21.180
how much heat is there in the
beginning, you got that plus the

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:25.380
Q that you added and yet
you are back to where you are.

00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:28.228
Therefore, you cannot define
something and say that's the

00:18:28.228 --> 00:18:31.178
amount of Q in the system
because you're able to add

00:18:31.178 --> 00:18:34.230
Q to the system and bring
it back to where it is.

00:18:34.230 --> 00:18:35.969
What happened,
of course, is you added

00:18:35.969 --> 00:18:39.079
Q and you did some work.
But the point is you cannot say

00:18:39.079 --> 00:18:41.909
the Q here is so and so.
But you can say the energy here

00:18:41.909 --> 00:18:43.818
is so and so.
Because if you come back to the

00:18:43.818 --> 00:18:46.271
same point P times
V is equal to 3 is equal

00:18:46.271 --> 00:18:48.900
to RT and the internal
energy of a gas is proportional

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:51.650
to the T,
energy returns to the old value.

00:18:51.650 --> 00:18:55.660
But now I'm going to tell you
so listen very carefully.

00:18:55.660 --> 00:19:00.116
Energy is a state variable
because it comes to the starting

00:19:00.116 --> 00:19:03.420
value, if you come to the
starting point.

00:19:03.420 --> 00:19:05.799
It doesn't matter where you
wander off in the PV

00:19:05.799 --> 00:19:07.881
diagram.
Heat is not a state variable,

00:19:07.881 --> 00:19:10.315
there's nothing called a heat
at that point,

00:19:10.315 --> 00:19:12.410
because I am able to go on a
loop,

00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:14.955
change the value of Q or
add some Q to it,

00:19:14.955 --> 00:19:18.014
and I come to the same point.
So, there's no unique Q

00:19:18.014 --> 00:19:21.576
associated with that point.
But there is a new unique

00:19:21.576 --> 00:19:24.276
quantity S,
called entropy,

00:19:24.276 --> 00:19:29.105
which has a fixed value at a
given point and if you go for a

00:19:29.105 --> 00:19:34.016
little loop in the PV
diagram and you come to the same

00:19:34.016 --> 00:19:36.838
point,
S will return to the

00:19:36.838 --> 00:19:39.839
starting value.
So, who is this S?

00:19:39.839 --> 00:19:45.750
That S is defined by
saying the change in the entropy

00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:50.660
is the heat you add divided by
the temperature.

00:19:50.660 --> 00:19:53.922
In a tiny little process,
if you are at some temperature

00:19:53.922 --> 00:19:56.769
T, you add a little
amount of Q,

00:19:56.769 --> 00:20:03.169
keep track of all the changes,
and that change will be zero,

00:20:03.169 --> 00:20:07.400
as I showed you in this Carnot
cycle.

00:20:07.400 --> 00:20:11.252
You can show more generally
that if you take any path,

00:20:11.252 --> 00:20:14.886
not just the Carnot engine
bounded by adiabatic and

00:20:14.886 --> 00:20:17.781
isothermals,
but any path you take,

00:20:17.781 --> 00:20:21.560
you can show that the
∆Q added up is not

00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:23.404
zero,
but ∆Q/T,

00:20:23.404 --> 00:20:27.387
namely give a weighting factor
of 1/T to the heat you

00:20:27.387 --> 00:20:29.426
add,
then the positives and

00:20:29.426 --> 00:20:32.559
negatives cancel and give you
exactly zero.

00:20:32.559 --> 00:20:34.120
In other words,
Q_1 was not

00:20:34.120 --> 00:20:35.971
Q_2,
Q_1 is bigger

00:20:35.971 --> 00:20:38.125
than Q_2,
but Q_1/T

00:20:38.125 --> 00:20:40.691
_1 precisely
balances Q_2/T

00:20:40.691 --> 00:20:43.151
_2.
The heat absorbed at higher

00:20:43.151 --> 00:20:45.691
temperature if divided by
T_1,

00:20:45.691 --> 00:20:47.680
to compute the change in
entropy,

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:50.651
then in the upper part of the
Carnot cycle here,

00:20:50.651 --> 00:20:53.180
and the lower part of the
Carnot here;

00:20:53.180 --> 00:20:57.930
the two cancel as far as the
entropy change is concerned.

00:20:57.930 --> 00:21:01.045
So, entropy is a new variable;
it's a mathematically

00:21:01.045 --> 00:21:03.700
discovered variable.
What we find is that if I

00:21:03.700 --> 00:21:06.143
postulate there's a variable
called entropy,

00:21:06.143 --> 00:21:08.772
the change in which,
in any process,

00:21:08.772 --> 00:21:14.150
is the heat transfer divided by
temperature, then that has the

00:21:14.150 --> 00:21:19.792
property that when you go around
on a loop you come back net zero

00:21:19.792 --> 00:21:22.273
change.
That means every point can be

00:21:22.273 --> 00:21:24.580
associated with a number you can
call entropy.

00:21:24.580 --> 00:21:27.946
Entropy is like a height.
Suppose you are walking around

00:21:27.946 --> 00:21:31.079
on some landscape,
each point is a height.

00:21:31.079 --> 00:21:34.690
You can walk here and there and
come back at every stage;

00:21:34.690 --> 00:21:37.303
you keep track of the change in
height if you come back to where

00:21:37.303 --> 00:21:39.460
you are, the change in height
will add up to zero.

00:21:39.460 --> 00:21:42.851
That's what I told you in the
case of a potential energy

00:21:42.851 --> 00:21:45.100
function.
It is just like a potential

00:21:45.100 --> 00:21:48.171
energy function.
Internal energy and the entropy

00:21:48.171 --> 00:21:51.591
are now state variables.
At every point the gas has a

00:21:51.591 --> 00:21:54.079
certain internal energy and an
entropy.

00:21:54.079 --> 00:21:56.829
They deserve to be called state
variables because when you go on

00:21:56.829 --> 00:21:59.360
a loop and come back they return
to the starting values.

00:22:02.549 --> 00:22:06.200
Now, you have no idea what this
quantity stands for;

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:09.460
you agree it's bizarre.
Work done, we understand.

00:22:09.460 --> 00:22:12.549
Heat absorbed and heat rejected
we understand.

00:22:12.549 --> 00:22:14.839
What is ∆Q over
T?

00:22:14.839 --> 00:22:18.089
Why is dividing by T
make such a big difference?

00:22:18.089 --> 00:22:19.520
Why does it produce a new
variable?

00:22:19.520 --> 00:22:22.368
We can see it is true;
at least in the Carnot cycle

00:22:22.368 --> 00:22:25.714
you can verify in detail that
the change in the total of all

00:22:25.714 --> 00:22:28.549
the ∆Qs over T
is in fact zero.

00:22:28.549 --> 00:22:31.111
So, we'll develop up a feeling
for what it means,

00:22:31.111 --> 00:22:33.299
but historically this is what
happened.

00:22:33.299 --> 00:22:36.375
People realized,
hey there's another state

00:22:36.375 --> 00:22:38.562
variable.
We introduce this new variable,

00:22:38.562 --> 00:22:41.110
we have no idea what it means
but it is a state variable so

00:22:41.110 --> 00:22:42.779
we'd better take it very
seriously.

00:22:42.779 --> 00:22:45.720
So, I'm going to tell you what
it means.

00:22:45.720 --> 00:22:49.074
But first I want you to get
some practice calculating the

00:22:49.074 --> 00:22:51.650
entropy change for a couple of
processes.

00:22:51.650 --> 00:22:55.633
So, let us take for example,
one gram of water,

00:22:55.633 --> 00:22:59.529
let's say m grams of
some substance.

00:22:59.529 --> 00:23:03.769
It's got some specific heat
C.

00:23:03.769 --> 00:23:07.906
And I'll change the temperature
say from some T initial

00:23:07.906 --> 00:23:09.670
for some T final.

00:23:14.130 --> 00:23:17.905
I do that by keeping the
system--starting the system at

00:23:17.905 --> 00:23:21.401
T_i and I
should never be far from

00:23:21.401 --> 00:23:23.651
equilibrium.
That's one of the conditions on

00:23:23.651 --> 00:23:26.223
this.
In fact, you can say it should

00:23:26.223 --> 00:23:28.890
be near, always near
equilibrium.

00:23:28.890 --> 00:23:31.732
So, the system starts at
temperature

00:23:31.732 --> 00:23:35.630
T_i,
I put it on a heat bath,

00:23:35.630 --> 00:23:39.559
which is infinitesimally warmer
than this and I let it heat up

00:23:39.559 --> 00:23:41.933
at that point.
Then, I put it on another

00:23:41.933 --> 00:23:44.190
reservoir, slightly hotter than
this one.

00:23:44.190 --> 00:23:48.609
At all stages I want the system
to be almost near equilibrium.

00:23:48.609 --> 00:23:51.783
In the sense of calculus you
can make the difference as small

00:23:51.783 --> 00:23:54.586
as you like provided you do
enough number of times and

00:23:54.586 --> 00:23:57.019
slowly I raise this guy from
here to here.

00:23:57.019 --> 00:23:59.838
At every stage the system has a
well-defined temperature,

00:23:59.838 --> 00:24:02.960
has a well-defined heat input
and I wanted to add it all up.

00:24:02.960 --> 00:24:04.799
So, what's the change in
entropy?

00:24:04.799 --> 00:24:09.124
S final minus S
initial is equal to dQ

00:24:09.124 --> 00:24:12.329
over T,
summed over all the parts,

00:24:12.329 --> 00:24:18.740
I should write this as an
integral, mC ∆T over T.

00:24:18.740 --> 00:24:23.381
Do you see that, dQ is mC ∆T?
But I got to divide by T

00:24:23.381 --> 00:24:26.897
and that integral is done
between some initial and final

00:24:26.897 --> 00:24:30.797
temperature and we can do this
integral rather trivially in an

00:24:30.797 --> 00:24:33.930
mC log T final over
T initial.

00:24:37.940 --> 00:24:40.802
That is the increase in entropy
of some m grams of some

00:24:40.802 --> 00:24:43.289
substance of specific heat
C that's heated from

00:24:43.289 --> 00:24:45.119
T initial to T
final.

00:24:45.119 --> 00:24:49.049
We're just getting practice
calculating this.

00:24:49.049 --> 00:24:50.910
We still don't know what this
guy means.

00:24:50.910 --> 00:24:52.750
So, don't worry about that
right now.

00:24:52.750 --> 00:24:55.938
If it did not divide by
T, what are you

00:24:55.938 --> 00:24:58.668
calculating?
mC ∆T integrated is

00:24:58.668 --> 00:25:01.400
just mC times change in
temperature.

00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:03.920
That's the old calorimetric
problem you did.

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:07.100
How many calories does it take
to raise the substance from

00:25:07.100 --> 00:25:10.819
initial to final temperature?
That you understand.

00:25:10.819 --> 00:25:13.479
When you divide by T,
something you don't understand,

00:25:13.479 --> 00:25:15.958
but anyway, let's make sure we
know how to calculate the

00:25:15.958 --> 00:25:18.617
increase in entropy when water
or something is heated from a

00:25:18.617 --> 00:25:21.829
lower to higher temperature.
If you cooled it from a higher

00:25:21.829 --> 00:25:24.571
to lower temperature,
you can use the same formula

00:25:24.571 --> 00:25:27.369
T_f over
T_i,

00:25:27.369 --> 00:25:28.992
but T_f will
now be smaller than

00:25:28.992 --> 00:25:30.488
T_i;
if you cooled it,

00:25:30.488 --> 00:25:32.815
if the log of a number less
than one is negative and the

00:25:32.815 --> 00:25:34.380
entropy changes it'll be
negative.

00:25:34.380 --> 00:25:39.242
So, let me do one more entropy
calculation that's going to be

00:25:39.242 --> 00:25:43.215
pretty important for us.
That entropy calculation is

00:25:43.215 --> 00:25:46.289
this.
Take a gas and watch it expand

00:25:46.289 --> 00:25:51.875
isothermally from some starting
point, at some fixed temperature

00:25:51.875 --> 00:25:55.954
T that goes from
V_1 to

00:25:55.954 --> 00:25:59.961
V_2.
What is the change in entropy

00:25:59.961 --> 00:26:01.840
when it goes from here to here?

00:26:06.180 --> 00:26:09.634
Again, the system must always
be in equilibrium or near

00:26:09.634 --> 00:26:13.152
equilibrium so I can plot it as
a point in the PV

00:26:13.152 --> 00:26:15.530
diagram,
so I slowly take grain after

00:26:15.530 --> 00:26:19.212
grain, do the whole thing I told
you, and find S_2 -

00:26:19.212 --> 00:26:22.720
S_1,
this is 2 and this is 1.

00:26:22.720 --> 00:26:27.072
That is equal to the sum of all
the heat transfers divided by

00:26:27.072 --> 00:26:30.410
temperature at every little step
of the way.

00:26:30.410 --> 00:26:38.003
But remember this is also the
same as P∆V over

00:26:38.003 --> 00:26:40.480
T.
Why?

00:26:40.480 --> 00:26:43.642
Because on an isothermal
∆U is zero,

00:26:43.642 --> 00:26:47.380
I repeated it many times but
you've got to know this,

00:26:47.380 --> 00:26:52.823
∆Q is P∆V.
But P over T is

00:26:52.823 --> 00:26:57.049
nRT over V,
∆V.

00:26:57.049 --> 00:26:59.980
You also want to divide it by a
T.

00:26:59.980 --> 00:27:04.590
Do you understand P over
T is nR over

00:27:04.590 --> 00:27:07.585
V?
So, P = nRT over

00:27:07.585 --> 00:27:12.163
V, I'm just saying,
PV is nRT,

00:27:12.163 --> 00:27:17.289
so P over T is
NR over V.

00:27:17.289 --> 00:27:20.821
Now, dV over V
when you sum or integrate will

00:27:20.821 --> 00:27:23.257
give you nR log
V_2 over

00:27:23.257 --> 00:27:24.780
V_1.

00:27:29.380 --> 00:27:32.387
That is the change in entropy
of this gas when it went from

00:27:32.387 --> 00:27:35.239
volume V and went to
volume V_2,

00:27:35.239 --> 00:27:39.089
at a given temperature.
You don't have to use calculus

00:27:39.089 --> 00:27:41.448
to do this.
Does everybody understand why

00:27:41.448 --> 00:27:43.349
this could have been done a lot
easier?

00:27:43.349 --> 00:27:46.120
You don't need to do the
integral here.

00:27:49.420 --> 00:27:52.899
Because I showed you in
studying the heat engine that

00:27:52.899 --> 00:27:56.712
the heat transfer Q is
nRT log V_2

00:27:56.712 --> 00:28:00.233
over V_1.
Since the whole process takes

00:28:00.233 --> 00:28:03.261
place at fixed temperature,
instead of dividing by T

00:28:03.261 --> 00:28:05.611
at every step,
you can just divide by T

00:28:05.611 --> 00:28:08.789
overall.
Just bring the T here;

00:28:08.789 --> 00:28:12.220
that's why this is a change in
entropy.

00:28:12.220 --> 00:28:14.784
In other words,
during the whole process you

00:28:14.784 --> 00:28:18.124
feel at one temperature then
integral of ∆Q over

00:28:18.124 --> 00:28:22.119
T is just 1 over T
times integral of ∆Q,

00:28:22.119 --> 00:28:24.589
which is the total heat
transfer.

00:28:24.589 --> 00:28:28.057
Anyway, this is the heat,
this is the change in entropy,

00:28:28.057 --> 00:28:31.272
S_2 -
S_1 is nR

00:28:31.272 --> 00:28:34.550
log V_2 over
V_1.

00:28:43.680 --> 00:28:46.760
Okay, so what have I done so
far?

00:28:46.760 --> 00:28:52.031
Let's collect our thoughts here.
